ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorescence spectra of the obtained nanoprobe (SiQDs-NH2-EDTA-Eu) and the ability for the detection of DPA are evaluated in this part. As shown in Fig. 7
                        , it is worth to note that SiQDs-NH2-EDTA-Eu presents the intense blue and green emission when excited at 280 and 420 nm, respectively. To design the ratiometric fluorescence probe and obtain the co-existence fluorescence of lanthanide ions and silicon quantum dots, 280 nm is chosen as the excitation wavelength in the following studies. Moreover, some new peaks located at 595 nm, 618 nm, 653 nm, and 696 nm in the emission of SiQDs-NH2-EDTA-Eu upon adding DPA solution (Fig. 8
                        ). These new emission bands are attributed to the f-f electron transition of Eu3+ (5D0-7Fn, n = 1, 2, 3, and 4). Its red emission became sensitive due to the bonds between DPA and Eu3+. Moreover, with the increasing the concentration of DPA (from 0 to 34 μM), the emission relative intensity of Eu3+ ions at 595 nm, 618 nm, 653 nm, and 696 nm significantly increase, while the emission in blue light region (around 442 nm) is slightly changes. Interestingly, the normalized relative intensity ratio change (I618nm/I442nm) versus the DPA concentration follows a simple linear eq. Y = 0.0295X + 0.0203, R2 = 0.9974 (Fig. 9
                        ). According to the equation DL = 3SD/slope (SD is the standard deviation of the blank sample), which was obtained by 10 consecutive scans of the blank sample. We calculate the detection of limit (DL) for DPA is 1.02 μM which is lower than an infectious dosage of the Bacillus anthracis spore (60 μM). As illustrated in Table S2, the quantum yield at 442 nm almost invariably for the silicon quantum dot before (18.1%) and after grafting (17.5%) with rare earth complexes. On the other hand, the quantum yield at 618 nm remarkably increased for SiQDs-NH2-EDTA-Eu with DPA, which indicated that the fluorescence of the Eu3+ was sensitized by DPA. Moreover, the fluorescence behavior of the probe is stable between 25 and 80 °C. The intensity of the fluorescence increased with the addition of DPA but remain stable between 25 and 80 °C (Fig. S3). It thus can be concluded that the temperature almost has no effect on the FL intensity. In addition, we make a comparison with other reported FL sensors as listed in Table S3. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first report of the combination of rare earth luminescence component with silicon quantum dots. Even though the detection limit for DPA is not the lowest, such probe with both two optical advantages of SiQDs and lanthanide ions can provide a new platform the DPA specific detection.
